english:
  title: A Letter to Hong, the Proofreader
  author: Lim Chun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I humbly present this to you. Long ago, Liu Zihou of the Tang dynasty said: "When a person enjoys honor and prominence, they receive favors without gratitude in their heart, and thus their repayment is meager. But when one falls into hardship and humiliation, unable to contain their emotion, they receive with reverence, and their repayment becomes immense. Therefore, the virtuous gentleman must strive for the great repayment and neglect the small. One who is grateful does not measure gratitude by the weight of kindness received, but by the different circumstances—urgent or leisurely—that attend it."

    Since I encountered misfortune, I have stumbled forward and backward, hiding and cowering, seeking aid from others many times. Yet all treated me as they would a cur or a pig, showing no regard. Thus I remained in the capital for five long years, growing ever hungrier and colder, with even my own kin refusing to open their doors. So I led my family eastward.

    There were those serving in the provincial administration—though I had not known them before, they were all scholars. Yet none inquired after my plight, and I myself was unwilling to impose my poverty upon others, so I dwelt in silence, never daring to present myself.

    When I heard that you had taken office in this province, I rejoiced, thinking: "Here is one who truly knows me. Surely he will treat me generously." Upon our meeting, you offered me a seat and spoke with me at length. Your courtesy exceeded what I had known before, and your words of comfort were sincere and earnest, as though you pitied my destitution and age. Then I understood that the great-hearted do not measure their regard by poverty or wealth, by lowness or height.

    I was moved to my depths, resolved to repay such magnanimity, keeping it ever in my heart, never forgetting it for a single day.

    Recently, in early spring, I traveled westward and returned. Passing through your territory, I could not stop to pay my respects and take my leave. Upon reaching the capital, the Emperor summoned me to visit the Heavenly Garden, bestowing great honors. Yet I did not join the ranks of guests offering congratulations. To the eyes of others, is this not neglectful, arrogant, and a breach of propriety?

    Yet I have reasoned thus: since you already know me well, you would not regard me as merely one who bows morning and evening with honeyed words and obsequious countenance. Moreover, you surely have confidence in yourself, treating me with far greater warmth than others. How could I be so mad or afflicted as to betray such trust? By observing how you treat me, I know you have not abandoned me.

    But my choices and preferences run counter to those of common men—such is my nature. Without your expansive heart and vast forbearance, who would forgive such eccentricity? Having received your recognition, yet unable to offer even the smallest service at your side, and unable to reveal the modest devotion in my breast, you would never know the depth of my gratitude nor my resolve to repay your great kindness. Thus I write these words.

    Your humble servant bows twice.
  footnotes:
    - Liu Zihou (柳子厚, 773-819) was the Tang poet and essayist Liu Zongyuan, known for his moral philosophy on gratitude and repayment.
    - The reference to the 'Heavenly Garden' (天院) and imperial summons suggests Lim Chun received an official appointment or honor from the court.
    - The author's apparent absence from the congratulatory gathering of guests reflects his character of independence and unconventional behavior, which he explains throughout the letter.
